What would you need to do to get the currency conversion microservice to talk to the currency exchange microservice?
You need to make a code change in the currency conversion microservice.

You need to go to the code of Currency Conversion Service, and you need to change the URL to point to the new URL of currency exchange microservice.

That's not good, why?

Because whenever we are talking about microservices, there can be thousands of microservices.Every time the URL of a microservice changes,you don't want to hard code it in another microservice.
You don't want to make a code change or a configuration change in another microservice.

We would want to build a solution where currency conversion microservice will be able to find the current location of currency exchange microservice automatically.

How can we do that?

That's where a concept called naming server or service registry comes into picture.

Let's say I have a few microservices, currency conversion microservice, currency exchange microservice, or other microservices.
Whenever a microservice comes up, what it can do is it can register with this service registry.So when currency conversion service comes up,it will register with this service registry.
If it has five instances, all the five instances will register with the name as currency conversion with this service registry.